			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=162#M162">22</a> of 94
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 922 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<P>Guys, try not to think of PvP on the micro level - i.e. class balancing (bards, SKs omg), resists, spells, etc.&nbsp; Those "fixes" - while maybe what Sony is looking for, will really not address the real issue&nbsp;relating to&nbsp;the decline of PvP.&nbsp; Class balancing, resist changes, and the like are short term fixes for a long term problem.&nbsp; Its like patching a dam with 300 holes with 5 extra bricks.</P>
<P>In all seriousness, the way to address the PvP issue is to create a new server that is capped at the Velious expansion (they could even release Velious after 3-6 months after it being up and just start with Kunark).&nbsp; </P>
<P>In one swipe that would create a pvp environment that not only fixes the vast majority of class balance issues, but if coupled with the proper ruleset (most SZ rules, single item loot, no no drop items except epics, minor xp loss from all deaths -- see my original post for detailed rules), they would create a&nbsp;server that&nbsp;has much greater potential to be dynamic, exciting and evergreen.</P>
<P>In all seriousness, Discord had so many characters the 1st couple weeks because it was an old world environment - people only dropped off the server as time went on because of the blantant hackers (early on) and the majority fell behind the few who dominated.&nbsp; The players will respond magnificently to an old world server - you could even charge a premium price.&nbsp; Many veterans would come out of retirement to play on that server, I can guarantee it, let alone all the new people it would attract.</P>
<P>Given the upcoming competition from WoW, it would pay to take a bold step - the short term financial risk could potentially easily be offset by the long term loss that will undoubtedly come from WoW.&nbsp; Make a move to capture a chunk of the "veteran" EQ crowd with a&nbsp;pvp old world server!&nbsp; Think in terms of opportunity cost; it would potentially cost far less to try this idea out then to lose a significant portion of the player base later on.</P>
<P>People would love it!</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV></DIV>	
